==Latin== {{wikipedia|lang=la}} [[Image:Island.jpg|thumb|īnsula in marī Adriāticō (an island in the Adriatic Sea)]]
===Etymology=== Etymology uncertain. Has been connected to Ancient Greek {{term|sc=polytonic|νῆσος|tr=nēsos||island|lang=grc}}, Armenian ''enez'', Old Irish and Old Welsh ''[[inis]]''.
Pokorny (1959) tentatively connects {{term|salum||the sea|lang=la}}, [[ellipsis|elliptically]] from {{term||terra in salo|land in the sea}}, from {{term|in||in|lang=la}} + {{term||salo}} (ablative of ''salum''), invoking Greek {{term|ἔναλος||maritime|tr=énalos|lang=grc}}.
{{unreferenced}} Other have explained it as kindred to {{term|solus|sōlus|alone, sole, only|lang=la}}; i.e. as a nominalized feminine adjective {{term||insulus}} reflecting Old Latin phrase {{term||en salos|in the open sea}}.
It has also been suggested that {{term||īnsula}} stands for *{{term||īnsōla}}, feminine adjective of *{{term||īnsōlus}}, thus standing for {{term||terra īnsōla|land by itself}}.
===Pronunciation=== * {{a|Classical}} {{IPA|/ˈiːn.su.la/|lang=la}} * {{audio|la-cls-insula.ogg|Audio (Classical)}}
===Noun=== {{la-noun|īnsula|insulae|īnsulae|f|first}}
# [[island]] # block of [[apartment|apartments]], usually for the lower class
